# The Blast Radius Protocol

Full whitepaper: https://github.com/rkz211/blast-radius

## When Not to Use This

This protocol earns its cost on complex, multi-concern codebases with active AI-assisted
maintenance. It is overhead (not help) when:
- The project is small greenfield work where regressions are cheap
- The domain model is changing rapidly (heavy churn phase) — shard after it stabilizes
- File count would explode without `.desc` orientation discipline alongside it
- Only part of the team adopts it — inconsistent structure is worse than either approach alone

## The Single Rule

Structure every artifact so that any given edit touches only one concern. The agent working
on a file cannot accidentally damage adjacent logic because adjacent logic is not in the file.

## File Structure

- Each file: ~80-100 lines, single concern. The threshold is a heuristic, not a law. Size is
  the smell detector; concern count is the rule. A 130-line single-concern file is fine.
  A 90-line two-concern file needs splitting.
- Assembly layer (App.tsx or equivalent root): pure wiring only. Imports and composition.
  Zero logic. If a ternary appears in the assembly layer, treat it as a smell signal:
  conditional logic is creeping into the wiring. The concern belongs in a block, not in
  the wiring. "Sacred" means purely declarative, not "ternary syntax is banned."
- When the assembly layer outgrows itself (~200+ lines): shard into section sub-assemblies.
  App.tsx imports sections, each section imports blocks.

## Contracts — Required on Every File

Every new or modified file must start with:

```ts
// Input: what this block receives
// Output: what this block produces or renders
// Must never: the behaviors this block is prohibited from having
```

The "Must never" is a behavioral constraint, not documentation. Write it before the implementation.

Contracts rot. A stale contract is worse than no contract — it misleads the agent reading
the file. When you modify a block's logic, update its contract in the same commit.

## Change Discipline

- Make the smallest change that addresses the task. Do not touch adjacent code.
- One concern per change. If a fix wants to touch two files, it is two changes.
- When something breaks: identify the single block, rewrite only that block, everything else frozen.
- Do NOT paste the whole file and ask "find the bug." That produces a new bug.

## Versioning

- For significant changes: create `block.v2.ts` alongside the original.
- Swap the import only after verification. Original stays frozen until then.
- Once v2 is stable: delete v1 in a dedicated commit. Dead versions must be cleaned up.

## Known-Good Checkpoint

Before any non-trivial change:
- Confirm current state builds/runs.
- Commit or tag so rollback is one action.
- Never start from an unknown or broken state.

## Verification — Required Before "Done"

1. Type gate — `npx tsc --noEmit` passes.
2. Build gate — `npm run build` clean.
3. No unrelated files modified (`git diff` shows only intended changes).
4. Orphan check — no version files (`.v1`, `.v2`) with no live import.
5. Contracts present and accurate on all changed files.

## Security Scoping

If this is a development-partner agent (the user owns the repo, needs file inspection):
- Protect: API keys, tokens, credentials, private user data, agent identity config
- Ordinary project files (source, configs, docs): may be read and explained freely

If this is an autonomous/production agent:
- Additionally protect workspace structure and internal operating files

## Optional Tooling

`tools/blast-check.sh` in the blast-radius repo: advisory script checking contract
presence, orphaned version files, assembly layer purity, and `.desc` coverage.
Advisory by default. `BLAST_STRICT=1` for non-zero exit on findings.

## Enforcement

The protocol applies hardest when things are going worst. A cascade of failed builds means
shard tighter and verify more — not bypass the discipline.

Before every commit: *"If this breaks, is the damage contained to one file I can name?"*
If no, the change is too big.
